node.text: I wrote this poem as a letter to my sixteen year old self, a reminder that anyone who treated me like this was not worth my time. I shared it on the internet as advice to teenage girls navigating their way through love with boys, a reminder that their lives are about so much more than those boys. Your teenage years are for friendship and discovering yourself and the marvellous things you can create and all the adventures to have. Do not let them be consumed by your dotage of another human being. Music by Dexter Britain. Videos from Pexels.com. #poetry #spokenword

node.text:
TW: mentions of eating disorders, fatphobia.

One of the subjects I touch on in my YA novel in verse is the concept of eating disorders and fatphobia. How pervasive it is and how harmful it is, how it can be passed down from mother to daughter, impossible beauty standards and how they hurt women and femme identifying people and keep hurting us through our  lives. Our society is structured in a way that we are never allowed to feel happy within our own skin, entire industries are made to keep us feeling uncomfortable or unhappy and I remember as a teenager and a young woman in my twenties, my experience with this was deeply damaging - I stopped eating at one point and became so thin, I couldn’t sleep on my side at night because my hip bones made it so uncomfortable. Rising against this takes a huge amount of  inner work and unlearning - which is why people say self love is a powerful revolution. The poem after, a poem I wrote for the @i_weigh movement is all about self love. Paro, my teenage protagonist takes this journey to find her divine self holding the hand of a goddess - for me, it was poems that got me through. I hope that you understand that you are worthy of love just as you are, that one difficult days you are gentle with yourself and your body. You deserve peace and kindness. #thegirlandthegoddess #poetry #nikitagill #selflove

node.text: I took some time away to do other things because I was getting really overwhelmed being very online. I share a lot of vulnerable things and I think I struggle with how volatile digital spaces are. For artists, it’s important to have the time to think about what we create and spend time working on our passions away in the silence of things. I read a LOT of great books, spent time with people I love and spent some time working on causes I love because it gives me space for healing. I hope you take the time for yourself too if you can. Take breaks and don’t beat yourself up for not posting often. Your work is so important and needed, especially now, as an artist - regardless of whether it is on social or not. YOU are so important and needed as an artist. I hope you remember that and look after your mental health. ❤️ #tweets #mentalhealth #artists

node.text: #AD - I was delighted to be commissioned to write a poem about this summer by @hendricksgin , my favourite gin brand. The poem is about how special and different this summer is for us in the U.K.- how the moments we used to take for granted are transformed into something magical after the difficult year we have had. And even though we can only meet in small groups with adequate measures to keep everyone safe, the company of the ones we love isn’t something we will ever take for granted again. So let’s escape the conventional and embrace the delectable! I got to work with a team of brilliant women to create this poem which can be heard on Spotify now! Go to my stories to hear a special reading! #SummerEscape #hendricksgin #CucumberLemonade

node.text: So here is the thing: people - women, girls, LGBTQ+ folks specifically are taught shame from an early age. The way we are expected to cope under the pressures of a culture that controls us via shame is infinitely harmful for our mental health and the way we perceive ourselves.  Undoing the damage shame does to the psyche is a lifelong process. Releasing and unlearning it is a step towards acceptance and self love. I hope you’re being kind to yourself my loves. #selflove #shame
